{
  "texts": [
    "To do so, we analyze normative ethics through the lens of computational complexity theory, which classifies problems in terms of the resources (e.g., time and space) a computer requires to solve them.",
    "While previous work have discussed computational limitations for moral machines more informally (Brundage 2014; Stenseke and Balkenius 2022), and provided embryonic complexity analyses of ethical actions (Reynolds 2005) and plans (Lindner et al. 2020), the computational complexity of ethics and its potential relevance for machine ethics remains largely unexplored.",
    "For instance, if artificial systems were to operate in ethical domains where time is of the essence (e.g., a self-driving ambulance), it is crucial that such systems can make efficient as well as competent ethical decisions.",
    "Furthermore, if human moral cognition is constrained by tractability (Van Rooij 2008), the analysis might also serve moral psychology and normative theory by constraining the space of problems an agent following a certain normative theory can be reasonably expected to solve.",
    "In the rest of the paper, concepts and theories from both moral philosophy and computer science are introduced and explained in a way that is friendly for readers with a limited background in one or both areas."
  ]
}